    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_531131501" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/531131501" />
    <a title="Maged" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17303461-maged"><img alt="Maged" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1369872998p2/17303461.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/531131501?book_show_action=true">Feb 09, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Maged" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Maged" href="/user/show/17303461-maged">Maged</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/15714287">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer531131501" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8783350064362896611"><br/>This book reviews the unknown pages of history of theft, looting and smuggling of the Egyptian antiquities over the last two centuries, which leads to the presence of more than half of Egyptian Antiquities abroad, under legal protection due to the system of &quot;sharing&quot; by foreign missions, displaying discovered antiquities for sale in addition to giving hundreds of rare antiquities to European Kings. <br/><br/><br/>The book consists of four chapters, dealing with the first emergence of the legal system in Egypt </span>
  <span id="freeText8783350064362896611" style="display:none"><br />This book reviews the unknown pages of history of theft, looting and smuggling of the Egyptian antiquities over the last two centuries, which leads to the presence of more than half of Egyptian Antiquities abroad, under legal protection due to the system of "sharing" by foreign missions, displaying discovered antiquities for sale in addition to giving hundreds of rare antiquities to European Kings. <br /><br /><br />The book consists of four chapters, dealing with the first emergence of the legal system in Egypt for the protection of monuments, from the first decree in 1835 which regulates the dealing with the monuments, during the reign of Muhammad Ali Pasha, the founder of modern Egypt, as well as establishing the first Museum of Antiquities, under the supervision of Sheikh El-tahtawi, who succeeded in making a decision to prevent smuggling and trafficking Egyptian antiquities.<br /><br />The author points out that, foreign consuls in Egypt sent Egyptian antiquities to Europe before 1835 without any legal ways or laws. Foreign missions required many privileges from Muhammad Ali Pasha, and his sons thereafter, when drilling and exploration, notably sharing the discovered monuments. <br /><br />Under the reign of khedive Ismail, a new regulation in 1874, allowed the regime of sharing monuments, in response to pressures from foreign consuls in Egypt, and discovered monuments became, under this regulation, divided into two equals, 50% to each party! In 1880, a decree gave permission to the export of Antiquities. In 1902, Egyptian Museum was constructed with the aim of preserving and protecting Antiquities than presenting them to visitors. And in 1912, the first integrated Act no 14 was released, it contains a definition of monument and controls its circulation and gives penalties for its violation. In the 2010 Act No. 3 was released, it prevents trafficking and puts end to selling and purchasing the antiquities detected, it fixed also intellectual property rights and trademark for monument's photos, but still contains gaps need to be filled.<br /><br />The author addresses in chapter II, exciting pages of history divide system, private property, trade and gift antiquities, he describes what tourists and visitors can see when visiting big cities all over the world, and how many monuments, obelisks, statues, stelaes can they find, when roaming in the Egyptian wings of the Metropolitan Museum in New York, the Louvre in Paris, the British Museum in London, Turino Museum in Italy, and how did all these monuments travel outside Egypt. The author thinks that policy which changes from era to era, controls everything and codifies legislation, and it is a major reason for the exodus of most of these antiquities abroad. Over a century, hundreds of thousands of monuments, travelled, some are rare and unparalleled.<br /><br />In chapter III, the author deals with the history of Egyptian monument's retrieve, he describes Geneva store which contains 400 pieces, and charged in the case of smuggling of more than 30 people with influence in Egypt, it returned to Egypt at the end of 2003. The warehouse of the Faculty of Arts in Maadi, which was stolen but his contents were delivered to Egypt at the end of 2008. <br /><br />The author points out the great importance of UNESCO's Convention on the prevention of the import, export and transfer of ownership of cultural property, and the protection of Antiquities in different countries, in retrieving Antiquities smuggled abroad. Among the hundreds of cases recover relics smuggled over the years, Egypt had three experiences with the Arab countries, Jordan, Tunisia and Saudi Arabia, he mentions also that these three tests were successful and productive. <br /><br />Chapter IV and last, indicates the incidents of theft of monuments throughout the 40s and 50s of the 20th century, which were concentrated in the Egyptian Museum in Tahrir square. In 1959, the entire Museum was stripped, and it appears that there are more than 300 artifacts have disappeared, and there are thousands of other pieces not registered at all. The Museum also displays years 79, 87 and 93 and 1997 to theft in the same manner. The last recorded operation to steal the Egyptian Museum was on the evening of 28 January 2011, Five men attacked the museum, broke some statues and stole about 27 pieces of one of the halls.<br /><br />But the most dangerous operation of theft in modern history is the one of Muhammad Aly's family jewelry. This one was very organized and took a lot of time to re cover objects, classify, to display and to store them, the jewelry are now after all these years displayed in Alexandria Jewelry Museum. <br /><br />It is about time now to develop a law to protect cultural heritage in Egypt and to impose regulations for the protection and circulation of cultural holdings, on the other hand, we have to encourage and uplift the Egyptian artistic and cultural taste<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="8783350064362896611" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


